    <stitle>ANTILOCK BRAKES/TRACTION CONTROL: BENDIX - PRINCIPLES, OPERATION AND SERVICE - OPERATION - EXCITER RING
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="operate" graphiccount="1">
        <title>EXCITER RING</title>
        <para>The exciter ring is machined to close tolerances and has 100 equally spaced teeth (
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0402903">Figure 3</hotlnk>). The ring is heated and then installed onto the wheel assembly.
            Then as the exciter ring cools, it shrinks on the mating surface of the wheel hub. As the wheel rotates, the
            100 teeth pass the sensor, each breaking the magnetic field creating the AC signal. One hundred cycles or
            pulses of the signal would indicate one revolution of the wheel. The signal is transmitted from the sensor
            to the controller.
        </para>
        <figure id="f0402903" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0402903" filename="../figg04/G0402903.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Figure 3. Exciter Ring</caption>
